While I doubt you will agree with my thought process, and accept that, I'll try to explain anyway. (And if you mean 'tell us what you think', that's fine. But if you use 'enlighten' as a jab with some pseudo-superior connotation, let me make sure I rise to the challenge; eat me. Take whichever of my replies fits how you meant me to interpret the wording of your post- in other words, don't be offended if you were not trying to offend)<br>
<br>
Here's my thought process. <br>
<br>
1. The mobs in question are beneficial to those who kill them. <br>
2. The mobs in question are relatively long respawns<br>
3. The mobs in question are desired content, proven by the fact that people want to kill them<br>
<br>
Therefore; each mob in question fits all the criteria for a rotation, to the letter. No argument can change that, so we'll take it as a fact. <br>
<br>
The only distinction, and one I've already made, is that after these mobs are killed just a few times, they provide the benefit to the guild that killed them. No argument can change that, so we'll take it as a fact, as well. <br>
<br>
That means that putting them on a formal rotation, would result in a list of guilds who are on autopass; there is no need to put him on a rotation if the rotation will soon be empty again. That isn't so much a fact, as it is a bit of logical development, but, eh, whatever. <br>
<br>
That does not mean, however, that the mob is unwanted; the desire to kill the mob does *not* have to come only from a guild able to kill him. I want to kill the AoW, and will soon, but I still have desire for the mob. <br>
<br>
This is where my thinking started to bend, a little. Desire is proved, if nothing else, by the replies to this thread and the want to team up on the mob. Desire is obviously present, so no amount of argument will change that either; therefore, it is a fact that desire is present. <br>
<br>
However, if there are instantly any number of entities that have the ability to kill the mobs by teaming, as there would be if a teaming rule was applied, then a rotation would be a necessary component as people tried to get their tries in at him. It may be a bit round-about, but it is nonetheless true that if many groups or single guilds can kill this mob, that many groups or single guilds will want to kill this mob now that they are suddenly able to. <br>
<br>
If many guilds or groups are able to kill the mob, he will become contested for a fairly long time. If you'll note, I left the word &quot;contested&quot; out of the requirements for a rotation, above. Here it is now: While it may be true that AD is not *currently* a contested mob, if you added a large number of guilds to the pool of guilds that can kill him, and in that large number of guilds, had people for whom AD's loot table would include some *major* upgrades, then killing him 'just for flags' would become less the primary reason, and more an equal reason, to kill him. <br>
<br>
Long respawns, valuable loot, contested mob... ding ding ding we have a rotation. The *only* reason that this mob would remain off a rotation, is that people would realize that by asking for one, they ruin it for themselves. Just as I said that a rotation should not be asked for with the intent to cockblock, a rotation should not be avoided for the purposes of twisting the rules to one's own benefit, because if a rotation was necessary, than by definition, anyone who wanted on in an unofficial team, would be breaking the rules of the RTA. This is not a case of a couple of guilds; there are many numbers of permutations that could arise and go in for a kill. <br>
<br>
Here's some basic figuring; I would guesstimate that any two King Tormax guilds would have the punch to kill AD. So lets list the KT guilds for a model. I then took off any guild that has killed AD already alone. <br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><br>
Now, decide before you read any further, if you don't think that these guilds are in an alliance if they team up to kill AD. <br>
</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
If they are an alliance, well, damn, that makes the conversation very short, doesn't it? <br>
<br>
As has been spouted many times before, you can't be an alliance for one thing, and then not for others. And don't scream &quot;but that's for rotations&quot; at me. It took me quite a while to understand why people were telling me that saying &quot;but they aren't on rotations&quot; was splitting hairs, and adhereing ONLY to the letter of the rules, and not the spirit by which they were created. I'll explain that too, but for now, back to the example. <br>
<br>
If they arn't alliances, well, I'll just pick who they team with. <br>
<br>
VoLS ED <br>
VoF  SoY<br>
CB  FS <br>
LoL SotE<br>
<br>
Ok, looks good, you have 4 new groups able to kill AD. No problem, that's only 9ish groups of people that want to kill him. That's not *too* conjested since he'll spawn 2 times a week, ish. You *might* need a rotation, but probably not at this point, so there's no rules being broken, by the letter of anything, great, off we go. <br>
<br>
But when you figure there are 27 combinations of any two guilds out of that short list of eight (and there are, don't make me do the diagram for it please), barring the ones that just wouldn't want to work together, I'd put a conservative estimate at say, 20 combinations that are workable to kill AD. <br>
<br>
Now, take those 20 combinations and add in the five guilds that kill him now, and you find you have 25 instances of a guild or two guilds that are able to kill him. Three day spawn, with 25 entities that could kill him? You know what that's called? <br>
<br>
It's called the Sev rotation. <br>
<br>
How conjested is that? And how possible do you think it would be to run it without a rotation on it?<br>
<br>
But wait Rogg, because the guilds would have to actually want to kill him that often, that would mean that guilds would have to be killing him for his loot, right? <br>
<br>
Hmm, you know, you're right Mr. Pre-Ssra, Pre Vex Thal gear'ed guild... what ever would they want to do *that* for? <br>
<br>
But wait Rogg, we can just make them say which one other guild they will always kill AD with, can't we, so there arn't 27 differant combinations and allow people to get in on many many kills?<br>
<br>
Sure can! In fact, that's how we recognize a formal alliance. <br>
<br>
Q. I want to team on the AoW. Why can't I?  <br>
A. He's on a rotation. <br>
<br>
Fair enough, I agree and that works for me. <br>
<br>
I did not understand, at first, that the actual words on a website rotations page do not matter as much as a convention in the game. <br>
<br>
That's why, for example, when I first asked about the situation, and didn't get a concrete answer, and saw no written rules about it, gave the go ahead to the officers in my guild who were going to lead our part of the joint raid. (As a note, keep in mind I don't speak for, or with, any representation from VoLS)<br>
<br>
There is indeed a 'rotation' on AD that currently exists. No, you won't find it on the rotations page, and if that is the only &quot;valid&quot; rotation that some people will recognize at all, I can't help you. But it does exist, if you believe it does or not is irrevelent at this point. <br>
<br>
The rotation does exist and it's very simple; don't kill him twice back to back, and if you're killing him, let members from those guilds who have already killed him alone know if there will be flags afterward so that their own guild doesn't have to raid to flag one person. It has established conventions between guilds, and if, as Gromm points out, that it is<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
A mere technicality that can be fixed in about 2 seconds if it must go to that. We are trying to discuss the issue without resorting to the 'quick fix'. *That* is why there hasn't been a request yet.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The situation we are in now, is one in which a mob that fits *every* criteria for a rotation, cannot be put on rotation without cries of cockblocking and 'keeping the little guy down'. Let me say that again: A mob that fits every criteria for a rotation, cannot be put on rotation without cries of cockblocking. <br>
<br>
I would like to restate that I want to team to kill the AoW, and that it's cockblocking if you don't let me. <br>
Can't? <br>
Why not? <br>
He's on a rotation. <br>
<br>
Works for me. <br>
<br>
The people you are arguing against now, and who I was arguing against not long ago at all, want to let people know why mobs have the potential to be on rotation, and if there is that potential, they should be treated that way. <br>
<br>
Sontalak has the potential for a rotation, still. If 2 smaller guilds were killing him so often that my guild couldn't get equal time on him, I'd want him on a rotation, and ask for one, and get one. Then those two smaller guilds would have to leave him alone, or 'formalize' the alliance. Either one works for me. <br>
<br>
Remember this?<br>
<!--EZCODE HR START--><hr /><!--EZCODE HR END--><br>
It took me quite a while to understand why people were telling me that saying &quot;but they aren't on rotations&quot; was splitting hairs, and adhereing ONLY to the letter of the rules, and not the spirit by which they were created. <br>
<!--EZCODE HR START--><hr /><!--EZCODE HR END--><br>
Ok, here's where I explain it. <br>
<br>
These situations have every criteria of a rotation; they work between the guilds like a rotation, and have their own conventions like a rotation. Everything about them, says rotation. <br>
<br>
Saying that they arn't a rotation because they don't appear on the rotation page, is like saying there are no commercials because they arn't listed in your TV Guide. <br>
<br>
These walk like a duck, quack like a duck, and look like a duck. <br>
<br>
It's a duck. Calling it anything other than a duck is completely self serving, and once I realized that, my thinking bent a little more. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
And if you now agree that you violated these supposed grey area rules, are you going to be punished for those grey area violations? <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Well, if there had been rules against it, grey area rules or not, then yes, I suspect my guild would be punished by whatever means the rules suggested. <br>
<br>
But since there were grey areas, and not rules, the 'violation' you're talking about is not to a rule, but to the spirit of the system. The RTA does not have punishments for 'spirit' of the rules issues. Moreover, since this discussion only recently occured, the actions of my guild at the time, obviously took place with out the information that comes from this discussion. <br>
<br>
Let me say it this way:<br>
<br>
Before I read and considered all the reams of arguments and statements that have come out of this, if you put me in the same situation, I'd make the same decisions, and we'd still have teamed AD. <br>
<br>
If you let me go back and make the decision again, having read all this and spent time, a good deal of time, thinking about it, I would have politely said no to the proposal to team up on AD, and not because of the argument it caused; I don't care about being in an argument as long as I am right. <br>
<br>
It would have been because I wouldn't have been. <br>
<br>
Long winded? Not done yet...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
Just becuase a few guilds may set up a system amongst themselves does not mean other guilds have to follow the same system. Just becuase the more progressed guilds have a system set up amongst themselves does not mean that it's an RTA system nor does it mean that other guilds on the RTA have to follow that system.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This whole thing that we work within, is the construct of 'a few guilds' that set up a system. <br>
<br>
I think the point that everyone forgets when we talk about rules and whatever, is that no one is saying &quot;you HAVE to do this&quot;. Hell, you want to go out and team up on current rotation mobs? Go nuts, no one and their dog can stop you. <br>
<br>
But you sure as hell won't be having a very happy environment, nor will you be creating one for everyone else. <br>
<br>
Every rotation is a system that started between guilds. Even the ones that didn't start with big guilds. Hell, watch me make a rotation right now. <br>
<!--EZCODE HR START--><hr /><!--EZCODE HR END--><br>
Hey! SoY! I want a rotation on Sontalak. <br>
<!--EZCODE HR START--><hr /><!--EZCODE HR END--><br>
If I wasn't trying to prove a point, I'd have my rotation, right now. That simple; be in a guild that killed Sont, and ask for one.  <br>
<br>
And you're right; no one HAS to conform to the conventions, no one HAS to be a part of the system. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
What are these non rotation boss mobs u speak of i'd like some clarification on this?<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Sont, Talendor, Gore, Venril, Rumble, Doomshade, hell, there's huge amounts of them, LTK, Gozzrem, Telkonar, any of the WW dragons, Vindi, restless burrower, insanity crawler, Woushi, velk, any of the named in PoG except tunare, Faydedar (the real one, not the druid epic spawned one) the howling stones named, Chardok royals, ... there's more, I know, but I can't think of them right now. <br>
<br>
Anyway, yeah, lots of non-rotational content that some guilds consider the &quot;boss&quot; mobs of their ability, some guilds consider &quot;the average day at the office&quot; and some guilds say &quot;does that still spawn?&quot; <br>
<br>
For every guild that says &quot;Ralloz Zek down&quot;, there's a guild that is celebrating their first Gorenaire kill, and it's every bit as big and exciting to them. <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
And if we are making Rathe Rules off of what a FFA server does; we have issues. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Frankly, if there was a general feeling that 'teaming up on all mobs is fine', you're damn right I'd organize a 200+ raid on RZtW; do you think I don't want to be in the elemental planes? Sure, I wouldn't lead 200 level 50's on the AoW, because that's a whole big 1 loot; but man, you take 200 to kill RZtW, and you get 72 flags. Do it three times, and you're in like flynn. It's all about what the conventions of the server are. If the convention was &quot;go nuts on whatever&quot;, then people would go nuts on whatever. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
I hold our &quot;Ratheians&quot; to a higher standard then FFA server peeps. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Why? We're just a random mixing of people, same as any other (non-regional) server. I didn't pick the rathe cause it was civilized. I picked the rathe because I knew people on it. <br>
Our shit stinks just as much as the next guy's, server notwithstanding. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
The rotations help to do this, but in the end - Honor lies solely within the individual and guild, not through the Rotation system. I don't think that applies here.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Look, while it might be nice to picture the RTA and rotations springing into place as we all hold hands and sway in a circle of love, that's not the driving force here. This is an old server, with old guilds. The rotations and reservations make it possible for this old server to manage the number of people it has at the 'high' and 'middle' parts of the game. <br>
<br>
Honor is not the reason we all came together and built something that is a compromise for all, but makes for a more relaxed playing environment. Sure, we may be a server that prefers pure PvE and not PvAnnoyingPlayersvE, and that's great, but we are in this game for ourselves as much as any other server's people. <br>
<br>
We're just people; and people, when you tell them that they can do whatever they want, will do...whatever they want. <br>
<br>
Just because we have a stable(r) government for our society, does not mean that the people in it are anything but human beings. <br>
<br>
Be careful thinking that 'we're just better'. <br>
<br>
We're differant, but we could have been exactly the same. <br>
<br>
Yers,<br>
<br>
<br>
